  "why": "The paper explicitly identifies the fidelity of generated inputs, defined as \"preserving original semantics and looking natural to humans,\" as a core design criterion. To achieve this, the proposed method, DRFuzz, incorporates a \"GAN-based Fidelity Assurance\" component. This component uses a discriminator network, pre-trained on the original dataset, to learn the distribution of plausible, natural inputs. During the fuzzing process, every mutated input is evaluated by this discriminator, and only those deemed to have high fidelity (i.e., are consistent with the learned distribution) are kept. This mechanism is applied globally to all generated inputs, not just between successive steps, thus preventing the cumulative distortion or \"drift\" that can lead to unrealistic inputs over many iterations. The paper's ablation study confirms the effectiveness of this component, showing that it filters out over 20% of low-fidelity inputs and increases the proportion of high-fidelity inputs from 57.5% to 86%. This direct enforcement of naturalness by restricting the search to a learned plausible distribution across all iterations fully aligns with the 'High' plausibility standard.",
